						<div class="verses">
									<div id="vers144932" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">1</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And now, true to his undertaking, the Lord visited Sara and fulfilled his promise;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144933" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">2</div>
						<div class="vers-content">old as she was, she conceived and bore a son at the very time God had foretold.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144934" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">3</div>
						<div class="vers-content">To this son whom Sara had borne him, Abraham gave the name of Isaac,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144935" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">4</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and circumcised him, as God had commanded, when he was eight days old.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144936" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">5</div>
						<div class="vers-content">He himself was then a hundred years old; so great an age had he reached before Isaac was born to him.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144937" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">6</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And Sara cried out, God has made me laugh for joy; whoever hears of this will laugh (Isaac) with me.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144938" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">7</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Who would have thought, she added, that Abraham would ever be told, Sara is nursing a son, born to thee in thy old age?<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144939" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">8</div>
						<div class="vers-content">The boy grew, and was weaned; on the day of his weaning, Abraham made a great feast,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144940" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">9</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and Sara found the son of the Egyptian woman, Agar, mocking her own son Isaac.<a href="" class="inline-comment" data-comment-id="49">âœ»</a> Whereupon she said to Abraham,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144941" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">10</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Rid thyself of this slave-woman and her son; it cannot be that the son of a slave should divide the inheritance with my own son, Isaac.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144942" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">11</div>
						<div class="vers-content">At this Abraham was greatly distressed on his sonâ€™s behalf;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144943" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">12</div>
						<div class="vers-content">but God said to him, Do not take it to heart so, the boyâ€™s lot and the lot of thy slave; attend to all Saraâ€™s bidding, for indeed it is through Isaac that thy posterity shall be traced.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144944" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">13</div>
						<div class="vers-content">As for the slaveâ€™s child, I will make him, too, the founder of a great nation; he too is thy son.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144945" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">14</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So, when he rose next morning, Abraham fetched some bread and a bottle of water, which he put on her shoulder, and bade her take the boy and begone. Thus she left him, and soon she was wandering to and fro in the desert of Bersabee.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144946" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">15</div>
						<div class="vers-content">At last all the water in the bottle was spent, and she left the boy under one of the trees there,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144947" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">16</div>
						<div class="vers-content">while she went and sat down opposite where he was, at a bow-shotâ€™s distance; I cannot bear to see my child die, she said. And there, sitting opposite him, she wept aloud.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144948" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">17</div>
						<div class="vers-content">But God had listened to the childâ€™s crying, and now his angel called to Agar out of heaven. Agar, he said, what ails thee? Do not be afraid, God has listened to the crying of thy child, where he lies yonder.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144949" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">18</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Up, and take thy child with thee, hold him fast by the hand; I will make him the founder of a great nation yet.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144950" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">19</div>
						<div class="vers-content">With that, God gave clear sight to her eyes, and she saw a well that had water in it; to this she went, and filled her bottle, and gave the boy drink.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144951" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">20</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Thenceforward, God was with him; he grew up, and made his dwelling there in the wilderness, and became a great archer.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144952" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">21</div>
						<div class="vers-content">It was in the desert of Pharan that he dwelt, and the wife his mother chose for him was an Egyptian.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144953" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">22</div>
						<div class="vers-content">It was at this same time that Abimelech, with Phicol the commander of his army, said to Abraham, God goes with thee in all thou doest;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144954" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">23</div>
						<div class="vers-content">swear to me, then, in the name of God, that thou wilt do no injury to me, to those who follow after me, or to my race; that thou wilt repay the kindness I have shewn thee by like kindness shewn to me, and to this land where thou hast dwelt as a stranger.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144955" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">24</div>
						<div class="vers-content">That oath, Abraham said, I will take;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144956" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">25</div>
						<div class="vers-content">but meanwhile, he had a complaint to bring against Abimelech over a well where he used to draw water, that Abimelechâ€™s servants had seized by violence.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144957" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">26</div>
						<div class="vers-content">I have no knowledge, said Abimelech, who has done it; thou hast never told me of it, and I never heard of it till to-day.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144958" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">27</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So Abraham brought sheep and oxen, and gave them to Abimelech, and they made a treaty there between them.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144959" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">28</div>
						<div class="vers-content">There were seven ewe-lambs that Abraham set apart from the rest of the flock;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144960" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">29</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and when Abimelech asked what was the meaning of the seven lambs he had set apart,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144961" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">30</div>
						<div class="vers-content">he answered, Thy acceptance of these seven lambs shall be my witness, that it was I who dug this well.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144962" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">31</div>
						<div class="vers-content">That is why the place was called Bersabee, the well of the oath, because the two men swore friendship there.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144963" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">32</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Thus they made their treaty over the Well of the Oath,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144964" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">33</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and then Abimelech rose, and went back with Phicol, the commander of his army, to the country of the Philistines. At Bersabee, Abraham made a plantation, and invoked there the name of the Lord God eternal.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers144965" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">34</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And for a long time he dwelt on alien soil, in the country of the Philistines.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
							</div>
